<!-- This article was automatically created by [[User:polbot]] from http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=J000275. The prose may be stilted, and there may be grammatical and Wikification errors. Please improve in any way you see fit. -->'''Charles Herbert Joyce''' (January 30, 1830 - November 22, 1916) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Vermont]].

==Biography==
Born near [[Andover, England]], Joyce<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->Immigrated to the United States in 1836 with his parents, who settled in [[Waitsfield, Vermont]].
He attended [[Northfield Academy]] and Newbury Seminary.
He studied law.
He was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1852 and commenced practice in [[Northfield, Vermont]].
<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->State librarian for two years.
He served as district attorney for Washington County in 1857 and 1858.
<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->During the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] served in the [[Union Army]] as major and lieutenant colonel of the [[2nd Vermont Infantry|Second Vermont Volunteers]].
He resumed the practice of law in [[Rutland, Vermont]].
He served as member of the State house of representatives 1869-1871 and served as speaker in 1870 and 1871.

Joyce was elected as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to the [[44th United States Congress|Forty-fourth]] and to the three succeeding Congresses (March 4, 1875-March 3, 1883).
He was not a candidate for renomination in 1882.
He resumed the practice of his profession in [[Rutland, Vermont]].
<!-- A grammar fix may be needed here. -->Later retired and resided in [[Pittsfield, Vermont]], until his death, November 22, 1916.
He was interred in Greenwood Cemetery, [[Rutland, Vermont]].

